2. PROHIBITED USES

The Software, in whole or in part, in original or modified form, may NOT be
used, deployed, integrated into, or relied upon by any system, product,
service, research program, or organizational activity falling into any of
the following categories. This prohibition is ABSOLUTE: it applies even
under a paid commercial license, and any commercial license issued is
implicitly conditioned on continued compliance with this section.

  (a) MILITARY APPLICATIONS. Any system, component, infrastructure, or
      research program directly supporting:
        - the design, manufacture, deployment, targeting, guidance, command-
          and-control, or operational use of weapons or weapons systems;
        - armed forces operations, including logistics, intelligence,
          reconnaissance, simulation, or training that materially supports
          combat operations;
        - defense procurement, defense contracting, or arms exports;
        - autonomous or semi-autonomous lethal systems of any kind.

  (b) SURVEILLANCE AND POLICING. Any system whose purpose, design, or
      foreseeable application includes:
        - mass surveillance of populations or geographic areas;
        - tracking, identification, profiling, or behavioral analysis of
          individuals without their freely-given, specific, informed, and
          revocable consent;
        - facial recognition, gait recognition, voiceprint identification,
          or other biometric identification of non-consenting subjects;
        - predictive policing, social-credit scoring, or pre-crime systems;
        - automated immigration enforcement;
        - monitoring of journalists, activists, political dissidents,
          religious or ethnic minorities, or labor organizers.

  (c) HUMAN GENETIC RESEARCH AND MODIFICATION. Any system or research
      program involving:
        - non-consensual collection, analysis, or storage of human genetic
          material or genetic data;
        - cataloging or classifying human populations by genetic ancestry
          for purposes other than medical care of the individuals sampled;
        - eugenics, including selective reproduction, genetic ranking of
          populations, or "genetic enhancement" research;
        - heritable human genome editing for non-therapeutic purposes;
        - genetic discrimination by insurers, employers, or governments;
        - forensic DNA databases that include individuals not convicted of
          a relevant crime, or family-tree DNA searches conducted without a
          judicial warrant supported by probable cause.

  (d) SYSTEMS THAT VIOLATE HUMAN RIGHTS. Any system whose primary purpose,
      foreseeable use, or deployment pattern is to:
        - cause physical or psychological harm to humans;
        - deprive humans of liberty, due process, or rights enumerated in
          the Universal Declaration of Human Rights (UN, 1948);
        - facilitate human trafficking, forced labor, child labor, or
          modern slavery;
        - discriminate against individuals or groups on the basis of race,
          ethnicity, national origin, religion, gender identity, sexual
          orientation, disability, age, or political belief;
        - manufacture or distribute disinformation at scale, including
          synthetic media intended to deceive about real persons or events.

The Prohibited Uses listed above are illustrative of categories of use the
author does not consent to, and are not intended as a numerus clausus. A use
that is materially equivalent to one of the above categories falls within
the prohibition, even if not explicitly enumerated.

Note that the research-use carve-out in Section 4(b) does NOT override this
section. Research that itself falls into any Prohibited Use category — for
example, research designed to develop a weapons-guidance system, or human
genetic research without consent — is prohibited under Section 2 regardless
of whether its findings are published.

