4. PERMITTED FREE USES

The following categories of use do NOT require a commercial license. They
are permitted under the grant in Section 1, subject only to the Prohibited
Uses in Section 2 and the Redistribution Conditions in Section 5.

  (a) PERSONAL AND HOBBYIST USE. Use by individuals for personal,
      educational, recreational, or hobbyist purposes that do not
      generate revenue.

  (b) RESEARCH USE. Use in academic, scientific, or industrial research
      whose primary aim is the generation of knowledge, where:
        (i)  the research findings, methodologies, datasets, or
             conclusions are intended to be made publicly available
             (through peer-reviewed publication, preprint, conference
             presentation, thesis, technical report, open-source release,
             or substantially similar means) within a reasonable time
             after the research concludes; AND
        (ii) the Software is not directly incorporated into a commercial
             product, service, or system offered to third parties as a
             consequence of the research.

      This carve-out applies regardless of the organizational form of
      the researcher: universities, non-profit research institutes,
      government agencies, corporate research and development laboratories,
      and independent researchers all qualify. A commercial entity does not
      lose access to this exemption merely because it also conducts
      commercial activities, provided the specific use of the Software is
      in research as defined.

      Research use INCLUDES preliminary experimentation, prototyping, and
      proof-of-concept work conducted prior to a decision to commercialize.
      If a research effort later transitions to product development with
      intent to commercialize, the commercial license requirement in
      Section 3 applies from the point of that transition.

  (c) EDUCATIONAL USE. Use by accredited educational institutions in the
      course of instruction, including coursework, student projects,
      thesis work, and faculty-developed teaching materials. This
      includes the use of the Software in MOOCs, textbooks, and
      educational software, provided the educational content itself is
      not principally a commercial offering.

  (d) NON-PROFIT ORGANIZATIONAL USE. Use by registered non-profit or
      charitable organizations in furtherance of their charitable
      mission, provided the Software is not incorporated into products
      or services sold or licensed to third parties for fees that
      materially exceed cost-recovery.

  (e) INTERNAL EVALUATION. Use for the purpose of evaluating the
      Software's suitability for potential future Commercial Use, for a
      period not exceeding ninety (90) days from first acquisition.
      Continued Commercial Use beyond this period requires a commercial
      license.

  (f) GOVERNMENT USE FOR OPEN PUBLIC BENEFIT. Use by government entities
      in the provision of services that are made freely available to the
      public, provided the use does not fall within any Prohibited Use
      under Section 2.

  (g) OPEN-SOURCE PROJECT DEPENDENCY. Use as a dependency by other
      software projects that are themselves distributed under an
      OSI-approved open-source license, provided that any downstream
      Commercial Use of the combined work still requires a commercial
      license per Section 3.

